    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1978-03-10T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1978-03-10T00:00:00-05:00" n="82"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d82">
                <head>82. Memorandum From the National Security Council Staff Secretary (<persName
                        corresp="#p_DC_1">Dodson</persName>) to the Executive Secretary of the
                    Department of State (<persName corresp="#p_TPR_1">Tarnoff</persName>) and the
                    Office of the Secretary of Defense<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d82fn1"
                        >Source: Carter Library, <gloss target="#t_NSC_1">NSC</gloss> Institutional
                        Files (H-Files), Box 42, <gloss target="#t_PRM_1">PRM</gloss>–24 [2].
                        Secret; Sensitive.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1978-03-10">March 10, 1978</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Joint State–Defense Memoranda on Arms Sales to the <gloss
                            target="#t_ROC_1">ROC</gloss>
                        <note n="2" xml:id="d82fn2">Attached to <ref target="#d78">Document
                            78</ref>.</note>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <p>The recommendations of a February 28, <gloss target="#t_NSC_1"
                    >NSC</gloss>-chaired Inter-agency meeting on possible arms sales to the Republic
                    of China have been reviewed. You should be aware of the following decisions:</p>
                <p>1. The following requests by the <gloss target="#t_ROC_1">ROC</gloss> should
                    begin the clearance process this Spring, including an assessment of when the two
                    Howitzer sales could be accommodated within the arms sales ceiling:</p>
                <p>• 100 155mm self-propelled Howitzers.</p>
                <p>• 100 8-inch Howitzers.</p>
                <p>• 150 M–48 A–1 unserviceable tanks for cannibalization.</p>
                <pb facs="0339" n="300" xml:id="pg_300"/>
                <p>• Four PPS–43 mobile radar systems.</p>
                <p>• A low-altitude aircraft detection system.</p>
                <p>2. Consideration of the third Hawk battalion should be deferred.</p>
                <p>3. Major requests for arms (i.e., jet aircraft—F–4s, additional F–5s, or <gloss
                        target="#t_KFIR_1">Kfir</gloss> fighters—the Harpoon missile; or the
                    Maverick) should be the subject of a separate analysis and possible <gloss
                        target="#t_PRC_1">PRC</gloss> meeting.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_DC_1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Christine Dodson</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
